
[1]catastrophy

   CATASTROPHY, n.

   1. The change or revolution which produces the final event of a
   dramatic piece; or the unfolding and winding up of the plot, clearing
   up difficulties, and closing the play. The ancients divided a play into
   the protasis, epitasis, catastasis, and catastrophy; the introduction,
   continuance, heightening, and development or conclusion.

   2. A final event; conclusion; generally, an unfortunate conclusion,
   calamity, or disaster.
